caption: 📣 Big news - the Global Engagement Seminar: Me and My Robot is opening its special lecture series to everyone for the first time!Join the 2024 Jarislowsky Fellows, leading experts & practitioners in the field, as we explore the social, physical, and practical interfaces between humans and robots and what their presence in our everyday environments will mean for ourselves and society.All lectures are happening in Engineering 5, Room 3102 and include a talk and Q&A.🤖 Unfamiliar Intelligence: Art, Exoticism, Robots, and AI (Feb 7, 8:00-9:30PM)Ken Goldberg is an artist, inventor, and professor at the University of California, Berkeley. Along with his students, he researches geometric algorithms and machine learning for robotics and automation in surgery, manufacturing, and other applications.🤖 What Thriving Interactive Robotics Could Mean for Our Society (Feb 14, 7:00-8:30PM)AJung Moon is an experimental roboticist and Assistant Professor at McGill University. She investigates how robots influence the way people move, behave, and make decisions to inform how we can design and deploy autonomous intelligent systems more responsibly.🤖 Reading Robots (Feb 28, 7:00-8:30PM)Amelia DeFalco is a professor of contemporary literature and member of the Medical Humanities Research Group at the University of Leeds. Her work concerns posthuman approaches to care, vulnerability, materiality and touch in contemporary cultural narratives.🤖 Every Moment of Every Day: When Robots Become Environmental (Mar 6, 7:00-8:30PM)Heather Suzanne Woods is a scholar and researcher of digital rhetoric and Assistant Professor at Kansas State University. Her areas of expertise include memes, virtual assistants Siri and Alexa, online activism and social media, and smart homes.🤖 Robots, Regulation, and the Changing Nature of Public Space (Mar 20, 7:00-8:30PM)Kristen Thomasen is a leading expert in robotics law and policy and Assistant Professor at UBC. Specializing in drone regulation, her research focuses on the ways automation and robotic technologies in public spaces affect equity, accessibility, and privacy.

event_details.event_name: Global Engagement Seminar: Me and My Robot
event_details.event_description: Explore the social, physical, and practical interfaces between humans and robots

caption: Join us and campus wellness for speed friending! Thursday March 14th from 5:30 - 6:30 in POETS!Speed-friending is fun and friendly take on speed-dating, where the goal is to quickly make friends through engaging conversation. Participants will sit across from each other and have 5 minutes to introduce themselves and start a conversation. At the end of 5 minutes, participants will change seats and reintroduce themselves to a new person. This continues until you have met as many people as time allows. Bring your own inclusive and engaging conversation starters or use some of ours. At the end of the session, you can stick around and continue the conversation, or make plans to connect another day. It’s a fun and safe way to make friends from across the Faculty of Engineering.Registration linked in bio!

caption: Employees from the Canadian Blood Services are bringing the stem cell swab kits to Engineering 7 (first floor) on February 7th. In one easy process, find out if you are eligible and donate right on the spot. It’s that easy! ————————————In Canada, a patients search for a donor may start with family members, but less than 25% of patients find a match within their family. Most of the time, patients must rely on unrelated volunteer donors from a registry, often with a similar ethnic background to increase their chances of finding a match. Help them out on February 7th!

caption: The second seminar coming up this week is SUPER intriguing! 👾Simran is hosting the second this week to investigate the role of cerebellum during a cross-modal attention blink task between vision and touch, make sure you tune in to both this week! 🙌- --Presenter: Simran MughalDate: November 23rd, 2023 Time: 5:30PM - 7:30PMLocation: RCH 206 - - -Abstract: To achieve a unified perception of the external world and execute correct behaviours and or movements it is important to process different types of sensory inputs in (near-) unison to achieve maximal information of the environment. This is termed cross-modal integration of information. At any given time, the brain is exposed to a plethora of sensory stimuli and thus, relies on selection and task-relevance of information for successful integration. The concept of attention is not a singular system, but rather a collection of mechanisms and significant attributes within various perceptual and cognitive processes that enable the regulation of information processing. Interestingly, selection is one of the significant attributes of attentional control, through which the cognitive system determines the pertinent information for ongoing behaviour. According to current literature, there is evidence for the involvement of subcortical regions in attentional processing, such as the cerebellum. Traditionally, the cerebellum has been termed as an accessory motor structure and has been linked to motor control and coordination. Nevertheless, emerging evidence indicates that the cerebellar cortex possesses considerable heterogeneity in its anatomical and functional connections with regions outside the cerebellum.

event_details.event_description: Seminar on the role of cerebellum in cross-modal attention blink task

caption: Join us this Wednesday for this week’s first student seminar on the Visual Appearance of 3D objects in SR! 🪐🚀🔭-Date: Wednesday November 15th, 2023Time: 5:30PM - 7:30PMLocation: PHY 352 -Abstract: The strange visual appearance of objects traveling near the speed of light is one of the puzzling predictions of Einstein's relativity. This is because the well-known Lorentz contraction of an object in relativity does not capture how an object would look - it doesn't take into account the time light takes to leave the object and reach the observer's eyes. We will derive a modified version of the Lorentz transformation which includes the time delay between measuring and seeing, followed by simulations of different objects traveling at high speeds. We also consider luminous objects, using the doppler effect to colour various objects while moving. We then talk about accelerating objects, whose visual appearance to an observer becomes extremely strange. Finally, we present some ideas about simulating the appearance of objects traveling in a strong gravitational field, moving from special to general relativity.

event_details.event_name: UW Phys Club Seminar on Visual Appearance of 3D Objects
event_details.event_description: Seminar on the Visual Appearance of 3D objects in SR

caption: Join us for this week’s second seminar in RCH at 5:30PM 🔭🪐🛸!More info and abstract below: Date: Thursday, November 16thLocation: RCH 206Time: 5:30 - 7:30 PM- - -Presenter: Siddhartha BhattacharjeeTitle: The Conservation of Mass isn't Fundamental in Classical Mechanics- - - Abstract:  In this seminar, we explore how the conservation of total mass of a closed system can be derived from simpler notions, namely Noether's theorem and the principle of relativity. This will be done using the Lagrangian formulation of classical mechanics.

event_details.event_description: Seminar on Conservation of Mass in Classical Mechanics

caption: Join us this Wednesday evening to listen to Shaeer Moeed’s seminar this on Path Integrals and Statistical Mechanics this week! --Date: Wednesday, November 8th, 2023 Time: 5:30PM - 7:30PM Place: PHYS 352 More info:Path integrals allow us to extract equilibrium properties of quantum many body systems. In the past, they have to been used to further our understanding of superfluidity in condensed Helium as well as probe the quantum phase transitions in rotor lattices. We will first review the path integral formulation of quantum mechanics and discuss computational details pertaining to Path Integral Monte Carlo (PIMC) simulations. We will conclude with a discussion of recent work focused on optimizing the convergence of propagators used for PIMC. Time permitting, we will also examine the theory of superfluidity.

event_details.event_description: Seminar on Path Integrals and Statistical Mechanics

caption: 📣 Big news - the Global Engagement Seminar: Me and My Robot is opening its special lecture series to everyone for the first time!Join the 2024 Jarislowsky Fellows, leading experts & practitioners in the field, as we explore the social, physical, and practical interfaces between humans and robots and what their presence in our everyday environments will mean for ourselves and society.All lectures are happening in Engineering 5, Room 3102 and include a talk and Q&A.🤖 Unfamiliar Intelligence: Art, Exoticism, Robots, and AI (Feb 7, 8:00-9:30PM)Ken Goldberg is an artist, inventor, and professor at the University of California, Berkeley. Along with his students, he researches geometric algorithms and machine learning for robotics and automation in surgery, manufacturing, and other applications.🤖 What Thriving Interactive Robotics Could Mean for Our Society (Feb 14, 7:00-8:30PM)AJung Moon is an experimental roboticist and Assistant Professor at McGill University. She investigates how robots influence the way people move, behave, and make decisions to inform how we can design and deploy autonomous intelligent systems more responsibly.🤖 Reading Robots (Feb 28, 7:00-8:30PM)Amelia DeFalco is a professor of contemporary literature and member of the Medical Humanities Research Group at the University of Leeds. Her work concerns posthuman approaches to care, vulnerability, materiality and touch in contemporary cultural narratives.🤖 Every Moment of Every Day: When Robots Become Environmental (Mar 6, 7:00-8:30PM)Heather Suzanne Woods is a scholar and researcher of digital rhetoric and Assistant Professor at Kansas State University. Her areas of expertise include memes, virtual assistants Siri and Alexa, online activism and social media, and smart homes.🤖 Robots, Regulation, and the Changing Nature of Public Space (Mar 20, 7:00-8:30PM)Kristen Thomasen is a leading expert in robotics law and policy and Assistant Professor at UBC. Specializing in drone regulation, her research focuses on the ways automation and robotic technologies in public spaces affect equity, accessibility, and privacy.

event_details.event_name: Global Engagement Seminar: Me and My Robot
event_details.event_description: Explore the interfaces between humans and robots, their presence in everyday environments, and their impact on society.

caption: Speaker: Sarah CenDate: Monday, April 1st, 2024Time: 10:30 AM - 11:30 AMLocation: DC 1304Title: Paths to AI AccountabilityAbstract: We have begun grappling with difficult questions related to the rise of AI, including: What rights do individuals have in the age of AI? When should we regulate AI and when should we abstain? What degree of transparency is needed to monitor AI systems? These questions are all concerned with AI accountability: determining who owes responsibility and to whom in the age of AI.In this talk, I will discuss the two main components of AI accountability, then illustrate them through a case study on social media. Within the context of social media, I will focus on how social media platforms filter (or curate) the content that users see. I will review several methods for auditing social media, drawing from concepts and tools in hypothesis testing, causal inference, and LLMs.Speaker Bio: Sarah Cen is a final-year PhD student at MIT in the Electrical Engineering and Computer Science Department advised by Professor Aleksander Mądry and Professor Devavrat Shah.Sarah utilizes methods from machine learning, statistical inference, causal inference, and game theory to study responsible computing and AI policy. Previously, she has written about social media, trustworthy algorithms, algorithmic fairness, and more. She is currently interested in AI auditing, AI supply chains, and IP Law x Gen AI.#ai #MITResearch #TechEthics  #ResponsibleAI #MachineLearning #TechTalk #GameTheory #aiethics #FutureOfAI #innovate #DataScience #intellectualproperty #aigovernance #TechLecture #UniversityOfWaterloo #TechInnovation

event_details.event_description: Talk by Sarah Cen on AI accountability

caption: 🗓: Wednesday, March 20, 2024⏰: 11:00 AM - 12:00 PM📍: EIT 3142Meeting ID: 965 8623 2115Passcode: FIROOZI24Abstract: Generative AI offers the potential to empower autonomous robots with the ability(i) to connect abstract concepts to 3D scene geometry(ii) to enable complex intention prediction and collaboration capabilities for robots to interact intelligently with humans and other autonomous agents.However, there remain significant research challenges in how to integrate these generative AI technologies into the robot autonomy stack without compromising safety, reliability, and explainability. In this talk, I will present my recent research toward addressing these issues. In the first part, I will discuss how large pre-trained Vision-Language Models allow robots to connect abstract concepts to 3D scene geometry, enabling autonomous interaction with objects and 3D scenes. I'll demonstrate how language and feature distillation into 3D world representations, such as Neural Radiance Fields, facilitate robots’ open-vocabulary navigation and manipulation. Beyond interaction with objects and 3D scenes, robots must safely interact with other coexisting dynamic agents in the scene including other robots or humans. As they interact, they need to reason about and predict other agents' objectives and reactions. In the second part of the talk, I’ll delve into safe and intelligent multi-agent interactions modeled through distributed real-time optimization techniques such as model predictive control (MPC) and game-theoretic planning. I will detail how game-theoretic planning, closely related to distributed MPC, introduces an additional layer of abstraction to interactive autonomy by modeling agents' preferences and mutual influences. I will provide an overview of how to enhance these interaction modeling tools' capabilities with larg generative AI models. I’ll briefly touch on paths forward, including employing generative AI models like diffusion in distributed multi-robot learning to foster the emergence of cooperation; using gen

event_details.event_description: Talk on Generative AI for Robot Autonomy
